:: prologue-greg-office
<!-- EPISODE 1: The Deal -->
[img[src/images/scene01-greg-office.png]]

Greg doesn't write code. Greg has read about code in a LinkedIn carousel.

The fluorescent lights hum their hymn of mediocrity. Greg, VP of Engineering, leans back in his chair, vibrating with "AI leverage" energy. He’s the kind of man who thinks "Server-Side Rendering" is a vintage hobby, like restoring steam engines.

"Quarterly reviews, Devin. It's time to operationalize your evolution," he says, leaning in close enough for me to smell the Soylent and the desperate scent of a man who just finished a 'Prompt Engineering' seminar.

His eyes drift to my faded 2010 RailsConf hoodie, the one with the frayed cuffs and the ghostly outline of a Ruby gem. I can feel the weight of my 2,000-line `~/.vimrc` in my pocket, a digital rosary of broken Pathogen hooks.

"It’s got such a nice, 'historical reenactment' dignity to it. Very 'unscalable' chic. Now, tell me: why hasn't your output increased by 10x? The board is looking at our 'compute spend' and they're seeing a lot of... manual labor."


[[A) Sweat over the .vimrc I've groomed since 2004. ->path-vimrc]]
[[B) Rewrite the review system in Rust.->path-rust]]


:: prologue-walk-home
The evening air is thick with the smell of money burning. Not mine — not yet — but the premonition of it. My apartment building rises like a courthouse at the end of a long hallway, a "wrapper" of rent that I am desperately trying to keep intact. If I fail, the "unhosted" life isn't an adventure; it's a death sentence for the world I've built for Sarah and the kids.

I open the door.

Sarah is on the couch. Leg elevated. The silence in the room has a different texture than it used to. The kids are fighting over a broken iPad screen that my 2011 hardware could never hope to mirror. The mortgage statement sits on the counter like a small, polite suicide note, formatted in a font that's too modern for my taste—and far too expensive for my bank account.

She looks up. "The car was fine," she says. "The other guy wasn't."

Three months. No work. A three-car pileup that somehow involved no cars. The insurance is a fog. The savings account is a rumor. My neuroplasticity is reaching EOL (End of Life), and I'm still trying to solve a 2026 problem with a 2011 stack, praying that technical purity is the same thing as a survival strategy.

What do I do?
[[A) Clear the table. Grind Linear Algebra from first principles before Monday or die of a caffeine-induced heart murmur.->path-a-grind]]
[[B) Sell my IBM Model M and 1998 'Vim Power User' shirt on eBay.->path-b-liquidate]]
[[C) Create "The Guy" — a deep-fake LinkedIn and a CV written in the language of the Snake. 🐍->path-c-create-guy]]
